data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3+ supports **ValueTuple-based `DynamicData`**, which gives you type safety and avoids `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key benefits:**
- **Type-safe** — no casts or `object[]` needed
- **Named fields** — tuples document each parameter
- **Compile-time checks** — mismatched types fail at build, not runtime

The test method signature stays the same; MSTest destructures the tuple into the parameters automatically.
